# Code Style Rules

> Stack-agnostic baseline. Where this project's stack has stricter idioms (a linter
> config, a style guide, framework conventions), the stack's rules win — record them in
> `CLAUDE.md` and treat them as an extension of this file, not a replacement.

## File Organization
- Prefer many small, single-purpose files over few large ones.
- Separate concerns: one module = one responsibility.
- Group by feature/domain, not by file type, once a directory grows past a handful of files.
- Keep a clear, discoverable entry point per module.

## Naming
- Be consistent with the conventions already present in the file/directory you are editing.
- Names describe intent, not implementation (`activeUsers`, not `arr2`).
- No abbreviations that aren't already established in the codebase.
- One naming scheme per kind of identifier (e.g. constants, types, files) — don't mix.

## Comments
- Self-documenting code is preferred over comments.
- Comments explain **WHY**, not **WHAT** — the code already says what it does.
- No commented-out code — that is what version control is for.
- Document non-obvious decisions, invariants, and gotchas at the point they matter.

## Structure & Readability
- Functions do one thing; extract when a function grows past a single clear purpose.
- Avoid deep nesting — prefer early returns / guard clauses.
- No magic numbers or magic strings — name them.
- Keep public surfaces small; export only what callers need.

## Error Handling
- Never swallow errors silently.
- Always include context when logging or re-raising (what was being attempted, with which inputs).
- Fail loud and early on programmer errors; degrade gracefully on expected/recoverable conditions.
- Do not leak internal details (stack traces, secrets, internal paths) into user-facing output.

## Formatting
- Match the indentation and formatting already used in the file.
- Where the project has an auto-formatter or linter, that tool is the source of truth — run it; do not hand-fight it.
- Newline at end of file.
